textBeforeTable: Excel | CSV Table 1: Domestic Airline Travel in May Among airports, Hartsfield-Jackson International in Atlanta continued in May to be the busiest domestic airport, with 3.3 million passenger boardings (Table 4). Among airlines, Southwest Airlines carried 7.1 million domestic passengers in May, the most of any airline (Table 3). The number of domestic airline passengers fell 2.0 percent in May from April (Table 2). Month-to-month comparisons may be affected by seasonal factors. Passenger trip length, the average distance passengers travel, was up 3.5 percent. Flight stage length, the average non-stop distance, was up 7.4 percent. Load factor, a measure of how many seats are sold and used, was up 0.4 percentage points. Available seat-miles, a measure of airline capacity, were up 9.3 percent. Revenue passenger miles, a measure of the number of passengers and the distance flown, were up 9.9 percent. In other domestic comparisons from May 2003 to May 2004: These passengers were carried on 802,602 flights, up 0.6 percent from the flights operated in May 2003. The U.S. Department of Transportation's Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS) today reported, in a release of preliminary data, that U.S. airlines carried 52.6 million domestic passengers in May, 6.3 percent more than in May 2003 (Table 1). 202-366-5568 Dave Smallen BTS 22-04 PDF Domestic Airline
